The H5N1 virus, formerly found only in fowl, has been identified as
the cause of nine confirmed cases of influenza in Hong Kong, 
Special Administrative Region of China, since May.  Three of these
cases have been fatal.  There are an additional three suspected 
cases currently under investigation.  This number is likely to 
increase slowly in coming weeks due to the enhanced surveillance 
activities now in progress.

(1) Male 5 months. Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 21 February 2013 positive for influenza A H1pdm09 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and H275Y mutation). No prior history of oseltamivir treatment before specimen collection. Clinically fever with respiratory illness. Discharged with only supportive treatment (no antiviral treatment given) 2 days after hospital admission.

(2) Male 23 years. Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 21 February 2013 positive for influenza A H1pdm09 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and H275Y mutation). No prior history of oseltamivir treatment before specimen collection. Clinically fever with respiratory illness. He was then treated with a course of Tamiflu and was discharged on the fourth day after hospital admission.

Male 2 year. Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 15 September 2013 positive for Influenza A H1pdm09 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and H275Y mutation). No prior history of oseltamivir treatment before specimen collection. Clinically fever with respiratory illness requiring hospitalization.  He recovered and had been discharged.

Male 31 years. Onset of fever and ILI symptoms on 23/11/2013. Oseltamivir treatment was started on 24/11/2013. Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 25/11/2013 was positive for Influenza H1N1 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and with 275Y mutation). He was discharged with continuation of Tamiflu for a total of 5 days. 

Male 13 years. Onset of fever and ILI symptoms on 28/11/2013.  Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 30/11/2013 was positive for Influenza H1N1 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and with 275Y mutation). No prior history of oseltamivir treatment before specimen collection.  Recovery was uneventful and he was discharged with no medication.

Male 84 years. Onset of fever and ILI symptoms on 17/1/2014. Nasopharyngeal aspirate obtained on 20/1/2014 was positive for Influenza H1N1 by culture, showing resistance to oseltamivir (phenotypically and with 275Y mutation). A course of Tamiflu was started after specimen collection. Recovery was uneventful and he was discharged on 22/01/2014.

The influenza outbreak in Metro Manila took place during the months
of July and August(week 25 to 32). Throat washings were collected 
from cases manifesting fever, headache, cough, and colds. Three viruses 
were isolated by the use of embryonated chicken eggs from fourteen 
throat washings, however, two awaits identification.

Summary data has been provided for the months of July and August:
Influenza epidemic in Metro Manila last July to August 1997.
Throat washings were collected from cases with fever, headache, 
colds and cough.
So far, three isolates were obtained by embryonated egg inoculation.  
One of the three isolates was identified by HI as of 03 Sept.,  as
A/Philippines/15 (H1N1).  Because of lower titers, the other two 
isolates await identification.

Influenza Surveillance August Summary - 1997:
A total of 419 swabs were sent for testing, 114 isolates were 
positive for influenza.  39 isolates of Influenza B were confirmed 
from several health districts.  75 isolates of Influenza A were 
also confirmed from some of those regions, three of which were

Summary of data is given for January 1997.
Only two B viruses were isolated.

Summary data for the season has been provided:
Seasonal increase in influenza isolations from April to June.
Most of the viruses were influenza A(H3N2), related to 
A/Wuhan/359/95(H3N2).
Influenza A(H1N1) viruses were isolated: 1 in February, 3 in July
and 1 in August.  All were related to A/Wuhan/371/95(H1N1).
Influenza B were sporadically detected from January to August.
Summary data has been provided for January to August, 1997.

2 cases of Oseltamivir resistance was detected 15 September 2010 and 26 September 2010 respectively. This was done using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) and further confirmed by sequencing and pyrosequencing. 

Prior to the detection of the latest 2 cases, there had been 6 previously detected cases of Oseltamivir resistance in the country which were included in the EIS report to IHR (WPRO).
